article.description: DeWanna Bonner scored 24 points to lead undefeated Auburn (No. 5 ESPN/USA Today, No. 6 AP) past Alabama 84-66 on Thursday night.
article.headline: Bonner one of five Tigers in double-digits as No. 5 Auburn rolls Alabama
article.linkText: Bonner drops 24 as Auburn remains undefeated
article.story:
AUBURN, Ala. -- Auburn took care of its biggest rival and started look forward to its big matchup with Tennessee.

DeWanna Bonner scored 24 points to lead undefeated Auburn (No. 5 ESPN/USA Today, No. 6 AP) past Alabama 84-66 on Thursday night.

Sherell Hobbs scored all 15 of her points in the second half and Whitney Boddie added 12 points and 12 assists for the Tigers (19-0, 4-0).

The Tigers host No. 10 Tennessee on Sunday, but didn't get caught looking past the Tide -- though Auburn was up only three at half on its last-place rival.

"I know we worked hard to get them prepared for this game, but kids are kids," said Auburn coach Nell Fortner, who refused to utter a word about Tennessee in the days leading up to the Alabama game. "Maybe the score at the end of the first half got them focused."

"You can't help to think about [Sunday]," Bonner said. "It's Tennessee ..."

The Tigers are off to their best start since 1988-89 when they won their first 29 games before losing to Tennessee late in the season. Auburn went on to win the SEC and advanced to the Final Four that year.

Alli Smalley chipped in 13 points for Auburn, which beat Alabama for the 10th time in the last 11 meetings.

The Tigers never trailed, but were unable to distance themselves from the Crimson Tide until midway through the second half, when they permanently extended their lead into double digits.

"I don't know what it is. People are just coming out and playing us really hard," Boddie said.

Varisia Raffington led Alabama (12-8, 0-5) with 19 points.

"This team has not been very successful in several years and the SEC hasn't been very kind to them," first-year Alabama coach Wendell Hudson said. "I think we are accomplishing one thing with this team and that is they are playing hard."

Auburn and No. 1 Connecticut are the only remaining unbeaten teams in the country.

Auburn struggled defensively in the first half, allowing the Tide to knock down five 3-pointers, and took a 39-36 lead into halftime.
